ProcedureHelp.#cdata:
Syntax: PROC FCMP option(s); 
    ABORT;  
    ARRAY array-name[dimensions] </NOSYMBOLS | variable(s) | constant(s) | (initial-values)>; 
    ATTRIB variable(s) <FORMAT=format-name ><LABEL='label’>< LENGTH=length>;  
    DELETEFUNC function-name; 
    DELETESUBR subroutine-name; 
    FUNCTION function-name(argument(s)) <VARARGS> <$> <length>
      <KIND | GROUP='string' <LABEL='string-2'>>; 
    LABEL variable='label'; 
    LISTFUNC function-name;  
    LISTSUBR subroutine-name; 
    STRUCT structure-name variable; 
    SUBROUTINE subroutine-name (argument(s)) <VARARGS>
      <LABEL='label'> <KIND | GROUP='string'>;  
    OUTARGS out-argument(s);

The SAS Function Compiler (FCMP) procedure enables you to create, test, and store 
SAS functions and CALL routines before you use them in other SAS procedures or DATA 
steps. PROC FCMP provides the ability to build functions and CALL routines using DATA 
step syntax that is stored in a data set. The procedure accepts slight variations of 
DATA step statements, and you can use most features of the SAS programming language 
in functions and CALL routines that are created by PROC FCMP. You can call PROC FCMP 
functions and CALL routines from the DATA step just as you would any other SAS function 
or CALL routine. This feature enables programmers to more easily read, write, and maintain 
complex code with independent and reusable subroutines. You can reuse the PROC FCMP routines 
in any DATA step or SAS procedure that has access to their storage location.

You can use the functions and subroutines that you create in PROC FCMP with the DATA step, 
the WHERE statement, the Output Delivery System (ODS), and with the following procedures: 

  PROC CALIS, PROC OPTMODEL, PROC GA, PROC PHREG, PROC GENMOD, PROC QUANTREG, PROC MODEL,
  PROC NLIN, PROC NLMIXED, PROC NLP, PROC GLIMMIX, PROC MCMC, PROC REPORT COMPUTE blocks,
  Risk Dimensions procedures, PROC SEVERITY, PROC SIMILARITY, PROC SQL (functions with array arguments 
  are not supported), PROC SURVERYPHREG, PROC VARMAX, PROC OPTLSO

StatementHelp.#cdata:
Syntax: FUNCTION function-name(argument-1, ..., argument-n) <VARARGS> <$> <length> <KIND | GROUP='string'>;  
        ... more-program-statements ...  
        RETURN (expression);  
      ENDSUB; 

Specifies a subroutine declaration for a routine that returns a value.

Syntax: SUBROUTINE subroutine-name (argument-1, ..., argument-n) <VARARGS> <KIND | GROUP='string'>;   
        OUTARGS out-argument-1, ..., out-argument-n;  
        ... more-program-statements ...  
      ENDSUB; 

Declares (creates) an independent computational block of code that you can call 
using a CALL statement.

Declares a hash or hash iterator object; creates an instance of and initializes data for a hash 
or hash iterator object.

Syntax: 
(1) DECLARE object object-reference;  
(2) DECLARE object object-reference<(<argument_tag-1: value-1<, ...argument_tag-n: value-n>>)>;

Specifies a group of statements to be executed as a unit.

Syntax: 
(1) DO; 
...more SAS statements...  
END;  

(2) DO index-variable=specification-1 <, ... specification-n>; 
... more SAS statements ...  
END;  

(3) DO UNTIL (expression); 
...more SAS statements...  
END 

(4) DO WHILE (expression); 
...more SAS statements...  
END;

StatementOptionHelp.#cdata:
Executes statements in a DO-loop repetitively while a condition is true. 

Syntax: 
DO WHILE (expression); 
...more SAS statements...  
END;

StatementHelp.#cdata:
Associates formats with variables.

Syntax: 
(1) FORMAT variable-1 <... variable-n> <format> <DEFAULT=default-format>;  
(2) FORMAT variable-1 <... variable-n> format <DEFAULT=default-format>;  
(3) FORMAT variable-1 <... variable-n> format variable-1 <... variable-n> format;

Executes a SAS statement for observations that meet specific conditions. 

Syntax: 
(1) IF expression THEN statement; 
    <ELSE statement;> 
(2) IF condition;

Associates informats with variables. 

Syntax: 
(1) INFORMAT variable-1 <...variable-n> <informat>;  
(2) INFORMAT <variable-1> <... variable-n> <DEFAULT=default-informat>;  
(3) INFORMAT variable-1 <...variable-n> informat <DEFAULT=default-informat>;

Syntax: LOSTCARD; 

Resynchronizes the input data when SAS encounters a missing or invalid record in data that 
has multiple records per observation.

Syntax: PUT <specification(s)><_ODS_><@|@@>; 

Writes lines to the SAS log, to the SAS output window, or to an external location that is 
specified in the most recent FILE statement.

Syntax: 

(1) RETURN; 

Stops executing statements at the current point in the DATA step and returns to a 
predetermined point in the step. 

(2) RETURN (expression);

 Statement within a FUNCTION-ENDSUB block.

Executes one of several statements or groups of statements.

Syntax: 
SELECT <(select-expression)>;  
  WHEN-1 (when-expression-1 <..., when-expression-n>) statement;  
    <... WHEN-n (when-expression-1 <..., when-expression-n>) statement;>  
      <OTHERWISE statement;> 
END;

SELECT groups contain WHEN statements that identify SAS statements that are executed when a particular 
condition is true. Use at least one WHEN statement in a SELECT group.

Syntax: WHEN-1 (when-expression-1 <..., when-expression-n>) statement;

Syntax: WHERE where-expression-1 
  < logical-operator where-expression-n>; 

Selects observations from SAS data sets that meet a particular condition.

Opens, manages, or closes the LISTING destination. 

Syntax: 
(1) ODS LISTING <action>;  
(2) ODS LISTING <DATAPANEL=number | DATA | PAGE > <FILE=file-specification>;

Produces a SAS data set from an output object and manages the selection and exclusion lists for the 
OUTPUT destination. 

Syntax:
(1) ODS OUTPUT action;  
(2) ODS OUTPUT data-set-definition(s);

Syntax: Opens, manages, or closes the PRINTER destination, which produces printable output.

Syntax: 
(1) ODS PRINTER <(<ID=>identifier)> <action>;  
(2) ODS PRINTER <(<ID=>identifier)> <option(s)>;

Syntax: ODS VERIFY <ON | OFF | ERROR | WARN>; 

Prints or suppresses a message indicating that a style definition or a table definition being 
used is not supplied by SAS.

Opens, manages, or closes the RTF destination, which produces measured output that 
is written in Rich Text Format for use with Microsoft Word 2002.

Syntax: 
ODS RTF <(<ID=> identifier)> action;  
ODS RTF <(<ID=> identifier)> <option(s)>;

Opens, manages, or closes the RTF destination, which produces measured output that 
is written in Rich Text Format for use with Microsoft Word 2002.

Syntax: 
ODS TAGSETS.RTF <(<ID=> identifier)> action;  
ODS TAGSETS.RTF <(<ID=> identifier)> <option(s)>;

Syntax: RSUBMIT <options>;  ENDRSUBMIT <CANCEL>;  
   RDISPLAY <CONNECTREMOTE=><server-ID;>  
   RGET <CONNECTREMOTE=><server-ID>;  
   %SYSRPUT macro-variable=value;  
   %SYSLPUT macro-variable=value </REMOTE=server-ID>;  
   WAITFOR <_ANY_ | _ALL_> task1...taskn <TIMEOUT=seconds>;  
   LISTTASK <_ALL_ | task>;  
   KILLTASK <_ALL_ | task1...taskn>;  

Marks the beginning of a block of statements that a client session submits to a server
session for execution.

Syntax: SYSTASK COMMAND "operating system command"
  <WAIT | NOWAIT>
  <TASKNAME=taskname>
  <MNAME=name-var>
  <STATUS=stat-var>
  <SHELL<="shell-command">>;  
  SYSTASK LIST <_ALL_ | taskname> <STATE> <STATVAR>;  
  SYSTASK KILL taskname <taskname...>;   

Executes, lists, or terminates asynchronous tasks.

Syntax: RDISPLAY <<CONNECTREMOTE=>server-ID >;

Creates a Log window to display the lines from the log and an Output window to list the output 
generated from the execution of the statements within an asynchronous RSUBMIT block.

Syntax: RGET <<CONNECTREMOTE=>server-ID>;

Retrieves the log and output that are created by an asynchronous RSUBMIT and merges them into the
Log and Output windows of the client session.
